Anonymous Sat 01 Feb 2020 00:11:49 No.28107603 Report
Quoted By: >>28107846
>>28107415
It's one of the theories on their hunting strategy. Some research has suggested their skulls were very durable and that they could open their jaws pretty wide. As far as bite force goes, it doesn't seem to be anything particularly crazy. So one theory is the hunted in a similar fashion to big cats, using their forelimbs to grasp smaller prey while they bite at it's neck. Either causing prey to bleed to death or break it's spine, as mountain lions do.

Aaaaand then you get into the other parts of the fossil record. We're pretty damn sure they actively preyed on stegosaurus to some degree, what with all the stego fossils that have allosaurus teeth marks in them, including the plates on their backs. And then there is the allosaurus skeleton with what appear to be wounds from a stego's tail spikes. We know they ate sauropods to some degree (teeth marks again) but it's a lively debated on whether they scavenged dead ones or actively hunted the giant dinos with walnut sized brains.
